00:14:43,178 --> 00:14:46,980
Our roundtable activity was to understand the struggles

250
00:14:47,200 --> 00:14:49,462
or differences and challenges of relocating.

251
00:14:50,082 --> 00:14:53,784
We had four volunteers who are immigrants, relocators,

252
00:14:54,484 --> 00:14:55,985
and people who have worked abroad.

253
00:14:57,092 --> 00:14:59,293
And they shared their personal stories and their struggles

254
00:14:59,373 --> 00:15:01,433
and their triumphs, all to create awareness.

255
00:15:01,834 --> 00:15:06,275
My takeaway was those who have to get visas, especially

256
00:15:06,315 --> 00:15:08,636
in the US, have a lot to worry about

257
00:15:08,696 --> 00:15:10,237
versus someone who's local who don't

258
00:15:10,257 --> 00:15:12,478
have to worry about that on top of their work.

259
00:15:14,278 --> 00:15:16,240
In February, for Black History Month,

260
00:15:16,280 --> 00:15:18,883
we sent out a newsletter educating our employees

261
00:15:19,023 --> 00:15:21,246
on why in the US this is celebrated.

262
00:15:21,887 --> 00:15:24,209
We showed 13th, a Netflix documentary

263
00:15:24,269 --> 00:15:25,290
at a bring your own lunch,

264
00:15:25,631 --> 00:15:27,713
and had a debrief at a lunch the week after.

265
00:15:27,733 --> 00:15:30,576
This thought provoking documentary analyzed

266
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:32,719
the criminalization of African Americans

267
00:15:33,239 --> 00:15:34,481
and the US prison boom.

268
00:15:36,212 --> 00:15:39,553
In March, for Women's Month, we sent out a newsletter,

269
00:15:39,993 --> 00:15:42,134
watched the documentary Misrepresentation,

270
00:15:42,154 --> 00:15:45,115
a film showcasing the horrifying realities

271
00:15:45,175 --> 00:15:46,875
of female media representation.

272
00:15:47,715 --> 00:15:50,016
Video games as a form of media is powerful

273
00:15:50,076 --> 00:15:51,417
in influencing our audience.

274
00:15:52,097 --> 00:15:55,078
As creators, knowing the misrepresentation of women

275
00:15:55,258 --> 00:15:57,538
is useful for being mindful on what we create.

276
00:15:58,418 --> 00:16:03,300
We had four women as well participated from Avalanche Studios at an external

277
00:16:03,360 --> 00:16:04,200
event in New York.

278
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:08,741
And a lot were happily surprised that, wow, there are women in Avalanche Studios?

279
00:16:10,321 --> 00:16:13,962
Also, the women in the company started Ladies Who Pastry.

280
00:16:14,862 --> 00:16:18,763
It's a half an hour get together biweekly of ladies to fika and chat.

281
00:16:19,283 --> 00:16:23,684
Fika is a Swedish tradition of a short break or downtime with coffee or snacks.

282
00:16:25,493 --> 00:16:27,834
In April for Spanish American Heritage Month,

283
00:16:27,935 --> 00:16:30,536
we taught our employees how to say the correct pronunciation

284
00:16:30,576 --> 00:16:32,076
of the Spanish words in our game.

285
00:16:32,636 --> 00:16:35,118
Just Cause 4 is set in South America.

286
00:16:36,058 --> 00:16:37,659
For May, we sent out a newsletter

287
00:16:37,779 --> 00:16:39,699
on Asian Pacific Heritage Month.

288
00:16:40,480 --> 00:16:43,461
One of my favorite activities is the Privilege Walk.

289
00:16:43,721 --> 00:16:45,002
You can search this on YouTube.

290
00:16:45,702 --> 00:16:47,603
I think it's the best way to talk about privilege

291
00:16:47,623 --> 00:16:49,103
without going into semantics,

292
00:16:49,644 --> 00:16:51,064
but just share personal stories.

293
00:16:53,193 --> 00:16:56,420
There are 35 questions, all of you start in one line,

294
00:16:56,601 --> 00:16:57,924
and depending on the question,

295
00:16:57,944 --> 00:16:59,607
you either step forward or step back.

296
00:17:00,229 --> 00:17:03,857
And the discussions after that was just priceless.

297
00:17:05,363 --> 00:17:09,466
Another thing that happened in May came from the feedback we got from women,

298
00:17:10,006 --> 00:17:14,349
which was the need for a training for respect in the workplace and assertiveness.

299
00:17:14,769 --> 00:17:19,633
This was in the height of the Me Too movement, and aside from enforcing a zero tolerance in the workplace,

300
00:17:20,133 --> 00:17:24,976
we got a trainer to equip the women and marginalize with skills to face this issue.

301
00:17:26,260 --> 00:17:30,505
My personal takeaway from this is that as women and minorities,

302
00:17:30,865 --> 00:17:33,608
we tend to say sorry way too many times.

303
00:17:34,248 --> 00:17:38,112
So at times, just avoid saying sorry and say excuse me.

304
00:17:38,152 --> 00:17:40,635
Like, sorry, I got this rule in book.

305
00:17:40,715 --> 00:17:42,817
Just say excuse me, I have this rule in book.

306
00:17:43,337 --> 00:17:44,458
It improves our assertiveness.

307
00:17:46,274 --> 00:17:51,456
In June for Pride Month, we had the roundtable where some LGBTQ plus employees volunteered

308
00:17:51,476 --> 00:17:52,456
to share their stories.

309
00:17:52,996 --> 00:18:01,339
Our goal was to normalize LGBTQ plus and hearing a familiar person's story was vital to this

310
00:18:02,179 --> 00:18:02,459
goal.

311
00:18:03,059 --> 00:18:06,820
Their comfort in coming out showed that they trust the organization and that they felt

312
00:18:06,860 --> 00:18:08,861
that they have co-workers who are ready to listen.

313
00:18:09,856 --> 00:18:12,137
We went on a three-month hiatus.

314
00:18:12,418 --> 00:18:14,339
In July, our studio closed for two weeks

315
00:18:14,419 --> 00:18:16,000
for our summer break tradition.

316
00:18:17,160 --> 00:18:19,362
August and September, we were extremely busy

317
00:18:19,422 --> 00:18:20,242
finishing the game.

318
00:18:20,903 --> 00:18:24,405
We restarted in October for Indigenous Peoples Month.

319
00:18:24,965 --> 00:18:27,287
We had a presentation at a company meeting

320
00:18:27,347 --> 00:18:29,968
on what and who are the indigenous people.

321
00:18:30,569 --> 00:18:33,090
We mindfully looked for ways to link our initiatives

322
00:18:33,210 --> 00:18:34,571
to be industry-specific.

323
00:18:35,232 --> 00:18:37,354
Again, info is not readily available.

324
00:18:37,454 --> 00:18:44,383
So for Indigenous Peoples Month, we looked for games that have Native Americans as protagonists

325
00:18:44,703 --> 00:18:48,168
and we made it available for employees to play during their break.

326
00:18:49,178 --> 00:18:52,419
Our final activity for 2018 was Disability in Games,

327
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:55,541
and we partnered with a non-profit organization,

328
00:18:55,721 --> 00:18:59,203
Able Gamers, to educate us on what we can do as developers

329
00:18:59,263 --> 00:19:01,204
to make games that are more accommodating

330
00:19:01,264 --> 00:19:02,524
to disabled players.

331
00:19:03,085 --> 00:19:06,306
They helped design the new Xbox Adaptive Controller.

332
00:19:07,567 --> 00:19:09,368
We invited them to our studio in New York,

333
00:19:09,548 --> 00:19:12,009
and we also hosted an event where we opened our studio

334
00:19:12,389 --> 00:19:14,630
to external folks so that they can spread the message

335
00:19:14,710 --> 00:19:17,352
of enhancing the disabled player experience

336
00:19:17,392 --> 00:19:18,452
so more people can play.

337
00:19:19,981 --> 00:19:22,741
New York recently passed a law to require an interactive

338
00:19:22,781 --> 00:19:24,822
preventing harassment training for all employees.

339
00:19:25,222 --> 00:19:28,603
We achieved 100% compliance in this educated our employees

340
00:19:29,583 --> 00:19:30,663
on preventing harassment.

341
00:19:31,283 --> 00:19:33,804
I believe that laws can help the DNI initiative in that,

342
00:19:34,244 --> 00:19:36,904
for instance, when you're requesting for more budget,

343
00:19:37,064 --> 00:19:40,285
if it's for compliance issue or purposes,

344
00:19:40,345 --> 00:19:42,785
then the budget is easy to get.

345
00:19:43,705 --> 00:19:45,566
The other New York law that I like a lot

346
00:19:45,666 --> 00:19:47,586
is making it illegal to ask candidates

347
00:19:48,006 --> 00:19:49,066
their current salary.

348
00:19:49,982 --> 00:19:53,923
This way employers just pay the market and not a previous salary, which historically

349
00:19:54,043 --> 00:19:56,103
is lower for women and minorities.

350
00:19:57,144 --> 00:19:59,524
And that was our 2018 calendar.

351
00:20:02,965 --> 00:20:03,445
Thank you.

352
00:20:06,746 --> 00:20:07,706
I wasn't expecting that.

353
00:20:08,026 --> 00:20:10,387
But you think you can do one activity from that list?

354
00:20:12,675 --> 00:20:13,055
Good.

355
00:20:13,836 --> 00:20:16,397
Our second goal was to improve our diversity hires.

356
00:20:16,917 --> 00:20:19,197
Improving our diversity numbers in the company

357
00:20:19,317 --> 00:20:21,878
is all good for creativity.

358
00:20:22,478 --> 00:20:24,159
A common thing to hear from naysayers,

359
00:20:24,219 --> 00:20:25,800
though, is that they're colorblind

360
00:20:26,440 --> 00:20:27,880
and that DNI is not a problem.

361
00:20:29,201 --> 00:20:31,381
And think that we lower the quality of hires

362
00:20:31,421 --> 00:20:33,122
when we start diversity hiring.

363
00:20:34,482 --> 00:20:36,883
Diversity hiring, however, is just

364
00:20:36,903 --> 00:20:39,144
to create a level playing field for all.

365
00:20:40,180 --> 00:20:43,002
Not empowering some while disenfranchising others.

366
00:20:43,542 --> 00:20:47,204
It is just casting a wider net and still hire the best out of that pool.

367
00:20:48,965 --> 00:20:54,128
To cast a wider net, one of the first few things we reviewed were our initiatives in sourcing and recruiting.

368
00:20:55,454 --> 00:20:58,897
First, I conducted an internal interviewer's training with tools and

369
00:20:58,937 --> 00:21:00,498
best practices for interviewing.

370
00:21:01,099 --> 00:21:05,323
Making hiring managers aware of their biases was a goal of the training.

371
00:21:05,863 --> 00:21:09,907
Interviewers are instructed to focus on competencies and potential of a candidate

372
00:21:10,007 --> 00:21:12,409
versus hiring how they normally used to,

373
00:21:12,469 --> 00:21:16,813
which is usually hiring someone who looks like them and are like them.

374
00:21:17,674 --> 00:21:20,516
To expect change, you must change our interviewing habits.

375
00:21:22,125 --> 00:21:24,108
Second is better sourcing process.

376
00:21:24,268 --> 00:21:27,431
There's data to prove that updating the job descriptions

377
00:21:27,491 --> 00:21:29,833
to be gender neutral, providing a description

378
00:21:30,134 --> 00:21:33,277
of what the role is, versus itemizing required

379
00:21:33,337 --> 00:21:35,339
qualifications increases the likelihood

380
00:21:35,499 --> 00:21:36,701
that females would apply.

381
00:21:37,682 --> 00:21:41,766
Best practices include avoiding ninja or bro language

382
00:21:42,186 --> 00:21:44,789
and painting a culture of just always partying and drinking.

383
00:21:46,250 --> 00:21:50,656
Discovering new job sites to post our jobs that would have different reach was another thing we did.

384
00:21:51,157 --> 00:21:56,484
We also increased our referral bonus. We saved on recruitment fees and got quality candidates from referrals.

385
00:21:58,126 --> 00:22:04,794
Third, we are aware that the first thing that candidates look at specifically in the U.S. to find out about the company is Glassdoor.

386
00:22:05,833 --> 00:22:09,756
They are known as the quote unquote enemy of the company, most companies.

387
00:22:10,396 --> 00:22:14,119
We partnered with them instead to make sure that information on Glassdoor about

388
00:22:14,299 --> 00:22:15,640
Avalanche Studios is accurate.

389
00:22:16,100 --> 00:22:19,063
A few of easy updates are correcting what our benefits are and

390
00:22:19,103 --> 00:22:20,464
sharing our activities and news.

391
00:22:21,144 --> 00:22:24,387
Candidates find out about our commitment to work life balance, and

392
00:22:24,407 --> 00:22:27,389
this is attractive to women and those with families.

393
00:22:28,169 --> 00:22:31,592
We continue to work on what needs improvement based on reviews, and

394
00:22:31,632 --> 00:22:35,215
increase our engagement by replying to reviews, good or bad.

395
00:22:37,072 --> 00:22:39,412
The next two actions are for long-term results.

396
00:22:40,233 --> 00:22:41,693
We increased our studio visits.

397
00:22:41,893 --> 00:22:44,894
We accommodated requests for more schools and students

398
00:22:44,934 --> 00:22:48,195
to come to the studio, meet and greet the developers,

399
00:22:48,215 --> 00:22:51,636
and know that making video games is a real job

400
00:22:51,676 --> 00:22:52,377
that they can have.

401
00:22:53,349 --> 00:22:56,392
Same goal of Take Your Kids to Work Day on a grander scale.

402
00:22:57,012 --> 00:23:00,897
The visit includes basic information on what are the different roles that they can be on

403
00:23:00,917 --> 00:23:06,422
a AAA project, and the tools or software that they can start learning and enhancing.

404
00:23:07,043 --> 00:23:11,408
It is heartwarming to inspire and motivate young, underprivileged, diverse kids to pursue

405
00:23:11,428 --> 00:23:12,709
their passion in video games.

406
00:23:13,430 --> 00:23:17,373
We believe that we can have a more diverse pool of candidates in the future.

407
00:23:17,754 --> 00:23:21,076
When we start educating a more diverse group of youngsters,

408
00:23:21,437 --> 00:23:25,540
that video game making is a wonderful possibility and career for everyone.

409
00:23:27,042 --> 00:23:31,145
Just two weeks ago, there were ten year olds who come to the studio and

410
00:23:31,165 --> 00:23:32,366
want to learn programming.

411
00:23:32,526 --> 00:23:35,369
And it blew my mind because their questions are about C++.

412
00:23:36,089 --> 00:23:38,351
And I'm like, what did I do when I was ten?

413
00:23:40,673 --> 00:23:42,934
Fifth, we extended our reach to minorities

414
00:23:43,014 --> 00:23:45,696
and marginalized groups by being present at their events.

415
00:23:46,136 --> 00:23:49,477
Examples are Game Devs of Color Expo, PlayNYC,

416
00:23:49,617 --> 00:23:52,378
AbleGamers, New York City Video Game Critics Circle,

417
00:23:52,499 --> 00:23:53,719
and Animation Project.

418
00:23:55,965 --> 00:23:59,567
We have improved our number of hits and minimize our misses in our activities as

419
00:23:59,607 --> 00:24:00,267
time goes on.

420
00:24:00,607 --> 00:24:04,109
I would like you to be aware and learn from our challenges as well.

421
00:24:05,049 --> 00:24:09,011
The main thing is there are not a lot of materials out there, nor

422
00:24:09,071 --> 00:24:10,092
guides to help us.

423
00:24:10,652 --> 00:24:14,774
Knowing what works for your demographics is the most important part.

424
00:24:14,934 --> 00:24:19,276
And knowing comes from conversations, surveys, asking questions,

425
00:24:19,396 --> 00:24:22,297
being curious, don't be afraid to look dumb.

426
00:24:23,907 --> 00:24:27,430
We often have production schedule conflict because we have a game to finish.

427
00:24:27,931 --> 00:24:31,674
The D&I team has to be mindful of that when planning for activities.

428
00:24:32,655 --> 00:24:36,097
In the beginning of this talk, I shared that D&I requires a lot of heart.

429
00:24:36,558 --> 00:24:38,299
There will be discouragements from others,

430
00:24:38,439 --> 00:24:40,921
primarily because of their hardwired biases.

431
00:24:41,542 --> 00:24:45,485
And thoughtfully looking for activities is taxing because we don't want

432
00:24:45,525 --> 00:24:48,128
to alienate others who are not yet our allies.

433
00:24:49,260 --> 00:24:51,820
We are restricted with not having the biggest budget

434
00:24:51,861 --> 00:24:53,601
in the world to do grander things.

435
00:24:54,161 --> 00:24:58,042
And we've also experienced members of our D&I team leave,

436
00:24:58,202 --> 00:25:01,163
and since it's a voluntary work, we don't hold them back,

437
00:25:01,703 --> 00:25:02,604
and it's never easy.

438
00:25:05,385 --> 00:25:07,805
It is hard work, time-consuming,

439
00:25:08,165 --> 00:25:09,366
but I'm proud to share with you

440
00:25:09,426 --> 00:25:11,767
that this is one of the most fulfilling initiatives

441
00:25:12,247 --> 00:25:13,987
I've been fortunate to be a part of,

442
00:25:14,127 --> 00:25:15,688
and I've learned so much.

443
00:25:16,915 --> 00:25:19,916
I'm happy to report that in two years, our different activities and

444
00:25:19,976 --> 00:25:22,176
partnerships resulted into the following.

445
00:25:22,857 --> 00:25:24,797
We have nearly doubled our women hires.

446
00:25:25,838 --> 00:25:30,139
Our active and sustainable D&I initiatives made noticeable impact to the lives

447
00:25:31,019 --> 00:25:33,240
of all employees, especially the marginalized.

448
00:25:33,940 --> 00:25:37,401
By just casting a wider net, we've hired our first woman programmer,

449
00:25:38,001 --> 00:25:40,642
promoted from within a woman to senior producer.

450
00:25:41,222 --> 00:25:43,463
We hired interns where three out of four were women.

451
00:25:43,663 --> 00:25:45,984
One of the women got hired as a full-time employee.

452
00:25:47,075 --> 00:25:49,877
Our retention rates for women has also been very high.

453
00:25:50,898 --> 00:25:51,639
True story.

454
00:25:52,639 --> 00:25:55,001
We were having our Coney Island trip in June,

455
00:25:56,102 --> 00:25:58,083
and one of the high tech companies,

456
00:25:59,144 --> 00:26:01,666
their names may have book and face in it,

457
00:26:02,826 --> 00:26:05,048
and they challenged us to a tug of war.

458
00:26:05,668 --> 00:26:08,130
They lost the first round and asked for a redo,

459
00:26:08,230 --> 00:26:09,871
asking for more women from our team.

460
00:26:10,572 --> 00:26:13,014
We still won the second round, but I'm more happy

461
00:26:13,034 --> 00:26:14,395
that we have more than enough women

462
00:26:14,435 --> 00:26:16,156
to even participate in a tug of war.

463
00:26:18,421 --> 00:26:22,163
We also have increased our people of color hires to half.

464
00:26:22,844 --> 00:26:25,766
Our activities have fostered a comfortable environment

465
00:26:25,806 --> 00:26:27,226
for employees to give feedback

466
00:26:27,306 --> 00:26:29,628
as to what we can improve in our games.

467
00:26:30,609 --> 00:26:33,550
One African-American employee suggested to change the name

468
00:26:33,590 --> 00:26:35,832
of one of our characters because the original name

469
00:26:35,892 --> 00:26:37,653
was offensive to African-Americans.

470
00:26:38,453 --> 00:26:40,535
A Hispanic employee suggested the initiative

471
00:26:40,555 --> 00:26:43,396
to teach our employee how to pronounce the Spanish words

472
00:26:43,437 --> 00:26:44,377
in our game correctly.

473
00:26:45,883 --> 00:26:51,984
This same comfortable environment led to LGBTQ plus employees saying that they're comfortable

474
00:26:52,024 --> 00:26:54,145
to be themselves and comfortable coming out.

475
00:26:55,065 --> 00:26:59,746
I haven't even mentioned the many ripple effect that we've had to everyone since we started.

476
00:27:00,186 --> 00:27:04,867
The bright ideas that come from our employees and connections we've made are priceless.

477
00:27:05,787 --> 00:27:08,348
These are tangible changes that fuel our efforts.

478
00:27:09,308 --> 00:27:14,609
2019 and onwards, we would like to continue on the journey to the ultimate goal of D&I

479
00:27:14,669 --> 00:27:15,610
protecting our games.

480
00:27:18,458 --> 00:27:21,123
If you could only take three takeaways from today,

481
00:27:21,143 --> 00:27:23,206
here's a summary of what you can bring back

482
00:27:23,246 --> 00:27:25,150
to your organizations depending on your role

483
00:27:25,570 --> 00:27:27,433
immediately when you get back next week,

484
00:27:28,135 --> 00:27:30,178
or unless you're on vacation next week.

485
00:27:30,899 --> 00:27:31,981
For those in management.

486
00:27:33,785 --> 00:27:36,545
Humility is the way for D&I to start.

487
00:27:36,925 --> 00:27:38,966
Without your support, D&I will not fly.

488
00:27:39,586 --> 00:27:41,186
Remain curious as to what would make

489
00:27:41,206 --> 00:27:42,406
your organizations better.

490
00:27:42,987 --> 00:27:45,167
Listen and commit to transform.

491
00:27:45,907 --> 00:27:48,048
For the content developers and creators,

492
00:27:48,448 --> 00:27:50,868
you are the most important part of the equation.

493
00:27:51,308 --> 00:27:53,029
You are most needed to be an ally.

494
00:27:54,449 --> 00:27:56,009
If you don't know how, ask.

495
00:27:56,549 --> 00:27:58,970
Keep the feedback loop by continuing to care

496
00:27:59,090 --> 00:28:01,030
and advocate for equity and equality.

497
00:28:01,986 --> 00:28:06,069
To my fellow HR, our people business needs a lot of heart.

498
00:28:06,749 --> 00:28:11,072
Our best ammunition is creating awareness, exercising compassion,

499
00:28:11,532 --> 00:28:13,593
and continued dialogue with our stakeholders.

500
00:28:14,734 --> 00:28:15,594
Easier said than done?

501
00:28:15,614 --> 00:28:16,255
Yeah.

502
00:28:18,016 --> 00:28:18,436
Worth it?

503
00:28:18,856 --> 00:28:19,297
It will be.

504
00:28:20,357 --> 00:28:22,499
Why am I here today?

505
00:28:22,519 --> 00:28:23,900
I'm not an expert.

506
00:28:24,320 --> 00:28:26,081
I don't work for the perfect company.

507
00:28:26,541 --> 00:28:27,922
Newsflash, there's none out there.

508
00:28:29,245 --> 00:28:31,107
I haven't been working long in video games,

509
00:28:31,187 --> 00:28:32,988
and in this industry, it seems to matter.

510
00:28:33,268 --> 00:28:35,809
The probability of being listened to

511
00:28:35,889 --> 00:28:38,311
is directly proportional to how long you've been in games.

512
00:28:39,071 --> 00:28:41,053
Budget and resources are always scarce.

513
00:28:42,654 --> 00:28:45,896
I'm here to share that in spite and despite

514
00:28:45,956 --> 00:28:48,157
of what we're up against, you can start an active

515
00:28:48,317 --> 00:28:50,719
and sustainable D&I initiative in your company.

516
00:28:51,459 --> 00:28:53,881
I hope you go back to work and implement ideas

517
00:28:53,921 --> 00:28:56,102
from the starter kit, no matter what your position

518
00:28:56,162 --> 00:28:56,822
is in the company.

519
00:28:57,703 --> 00:28:59,344
you can be part of the solution.

520
00:28:59,884 --> 00:29:03,205
It is an uphill battle and some days are more challenging

521
00:29:03,245 --> 00:29:04,846
that it's easy to not do it.

522
00:29:05,346 --> 00:29:07,227
There are days when we step back two times

523
00:29:07,607 --> 00:29:08,467
and we make mistakes,

524
00:29:09,007 --> 00:29:11,668
or others who we work with make it harder.

525
00:29:15,831 --> 00:29:18,132
There's a definite cost to doing nothing.

526
00:29:18,652 --> 00:29:20,953
With globalization and changing demographics,

527
00:29:21,373 --> 00:29:24,154
DNI is no longer a, aw, that's nice.

528
00:29:24,754 --> 00:29:27,715
It is a business strategy that every company,

529
00:29:27,775 --> 00:29:30,736
whatever their size is, must have to be competitive.

530
00:29:32,076 --> 00:29:34,397
Bring the starter kit to someone who gets it

531
00:29:34,977 --> 00:29:36,718
and also wants to do something about it.

532
00:29:37,498 --> 00:29:38,679
This can't be done alone.

533
00:29:39,719 --> 00:29:41,620
Who will you share the starter kit to?

534
00:29:43,995 --> 00:29:46,560
Together, we can all be the change

535
00:29:46,621 --> 00:29:49,566
that we wish to see for improving D&I in games.

536
00:29:52,031 --> 00:29:52,793
Thanks for being here.

